          "body": "The chapter closes with Solomon's maritime venture (8:17-18). He travels to Ezion-geber and Eloth on the Red Sea coast, Huram sends ships and experienced sailors, and together they sail to Ophir and return with 450 talents of gold. The placement is deliberate — after the worship section, after the completion notice of 8:16, the gold arrives. The Chronicler's sequence is theologically suggestive: worship first, wealth second. The gold that ends the chapter anticipates the glory narrative of chapter 9 (the queen of Sheba will arrive bearing more gold, 9:9) and confirms that covenant faithfulness produces material blessing — the Deuteronomic prosperity pattern (Deut 28:1-14). But the reader of Deuteronomy 17:17 cannot miss the undertow: \"nor shall he greatly increase silver and gold for himself.\" The Chronicler does not comment; he lets the number — 450 talents — speak."
